{{Reflist}} 

[[Category:Oceanography]]


{{philippines-stub}}

The '''Conrad discontinuity''' corresponds to the sub-horizontal boundary in [[continental crust]] at which the [[seismic wave]] velocity increases in a discontinuous way. This boundary is observed in various continental regions at a depth of 15 to 20&nbsp;km, however it is not found in [[Oceanic crust|oceanic]] regions.

The Conrad discontinuity (named after the [[seismology|seismologist]] [[Victor Conrad]]) is considered to be the border between the upper continental crust and the lower one. It is not as pronounced as the [[Mohorovičić discontinuity]], and absent in some continental regions.<ref name="Lowrie">{{cite book|last=Lowrie|first=W.|title=Fundamentals of Geophysics|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=1997|pages=149|isbn=9780521467285|url=https://books.google.com/?id=7vR2RJSIGVoC&pg=PA149&dq=%22conrad+discontinuity%22#v=onepage&q=%22conrad%20discontinuity%22&f=false|accessdate=30 June 2012}}</ref>  Up to the middle 20th Century  the upper crust in continental regions was seen to consist of [[felsic rock]]s such as [[granite]] ([[sial]], for silica-aluminium), and the lower one to consist of more magnesium-rich [[mafic rock]]s like [[basalt]] ([[Sima (geology)|sima]], for silica-magnesium). Therefore, the seismologists of that time considered that the Conrad discontinuity should correspond to a sharply defined contact between the chemically distinct two layers, sial and sima.<ref name="Kearey">{{cite book|last=Kearey|first=P. |author2=Klepeis K.A. |author3=Vine F.J.|title=Global Tectonics|publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]]|year=2009|edition=3|pages=19–21|isbn=9781405107778|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HYqZntfg25UC&pg=PA19&dq=%22conrad+discontinuity%22#v=onepage&q=%22conrad%20discontinuity%22&f=false|accessdate=30 June 2012}}</ref>

However, from the 1960s onward this theory was strongly contested among [[geologist]]s. The exact geological significance of the Conrad discontinuity is still not clarified. The possibility that it represents the transition from amphibolite facies to granulite facies [[metamorphism]] has been given some support from observations of the uplifted central part of the [[Vredefort crater]] and the surrounding [[Kaapvaal Craton]].<ref name="Muundjua">{{cite journal|last=Muundjua|first=M. |author2=Hart R.J. |author3=Golder S.A. |author4=Carporzen L.  |author5=Galdeano A.|year=2007|title=Magnetic imaging of the Vredefort impact crater, South Africa|journal=Earth and Planetary Science Letters |volume=261|issue=3–4|pages=456–468|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0012821X07004505|accessdate=30 June 2012|doi=10.1016/j.epsl.2007.07.044|bibcode=2007E&PSL.261..456M}}</ref>

