{{Italic title}}
'''''Des singularités de la nature''''' is an essay on [[natural history]] by the French philosopher and author [[Voltaire]], first published in 1768.<ref name="roe">{{cite journal|last1=Roe|first1=Shirley A.|title=Voltaire Versus Needham: Atheism, Materialism, and the Generation of Life|journal=Journal of the History of Ideas|date=January 1985|volume=46|issue=1|pages=65|doi=10.2307/2709776}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Carozzi|first1=Marguerite|title=Voltaire's Attitude Toward Geology|url=http://hdl.handle.net/2142/71029|publisher=University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign|accessdate=8 June 2016|format=PhD Thesis|date=1982}}</ref> In it, he defends [[Preformationism]], the idea that organisms develop from tiny versions of themselves.<ref name="roe"/> He defends the idea of a supreme being, and the idea that many features of the natural world have been made to benefit people, including noses for smelling and mountains for forming the landscape.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K126jf2DiRYC|title=Philosophers of the Enlightenment|last=Gilmour|first=Peter|date=1990|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9780389209102|page=144|language=en}}</ref>

